                                                                                    ('Nerve', '0515123463', 320, '9/1/1998', 94, 'In one of the early novels that established the author as a master of the whodunit, a struggling young jockey, isolated in a family of musicians, traces the source of his losing streak to something far more sinister than loneliness. Reprint.', 5.29, 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0515123463.01.THUMBZZZ.jpg', 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0515123463.01.MZZZZZZZ.jpg', 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0515123463.01.LZZZZZZZ.jpg'),
                                                                                    ('Wild Horses', '0425196747', 352, '5/4/2004', 60, 'Once a blacksmith, now famous and respected as a newspaperman, Valentine Clark knows everyone who is anyone in the racing world. Aged, confused, blind and dying, he harbors a daunting secret that he is desperate to be rid of. He makes his last confession to his visiting film-director friend, Thomas Lyon, whom in his delirium he mistakes for a priest. Unburdened and at peace, Valentine passes away, yet his legacy remains, guarded by Thomas.On location in Newmarket, Thomas is troubled by the old man''s secret. Seeking to understand this puzzling revelation, he uncovers a long-unsolved mystery that he soon finds is very much unforgotten. But as much as he wants to learn more, it seems he already knows too much. Imaginative and decisive though he may be, he will need superhuman courage and extreme cunning to stay alive.', 10.99, 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0425196747.01.THUMBZZZ.jpg', 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0425196747.01.MZZZZZZZ.jpg', 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0425196747.01.LZZZZZZZ.jpg'),
                                                                                    ('Driving Force', '0449221393', 384, '12/29/1993', 57, 'It''s life and death neck-and-neck in the stretch in this, Dick Francis''s thirty-first horseracing thriller.Young ex-jockey Freddie Croft owns a profitable fleet of horse vans that convey runners to the course. A man who has few illusions about racing''s smarmier aspects, Freddie is a stickler for security. But even he is startled by the violence that erupts when a hard, fast rule is broken: Never pick up a hitchhiker.In what will be the first of many ironies, the passenger - not the driver - turns up dead. And if one corpse is bad for business, what happens next could well be fatal: Freddie is swept unknowingly into the vortex of a malign conspiracy in which appearances deceive and the cost of being duped is murderously high. Tilting at the shifting shadows cast by his elusive adversaries, he must summon up extraordinary guile and courage to protect his enterprise - and save his life.Driving Force is Dick Francis at his most tantalizingly complex and dramatically propulsive - the kind of top-drawer suspense no aficionado can resist.', 5.7, 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0449221393.01.THUMBZZZ.jpg', 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0449221393.01.MZZZZZZZ.jpg', 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0449221393.01.LZZZZZZZ.jpg'),
                                                                                    ('Flying Finish', '0515125601', 276, '8/1/1999', 94, 'To escape the demands of his ancestral home, young aristocrat Henry Grey takes a dirty and demanding job ferrying race horses across the Atlantic by air and becomes involved in a crime syndicate. Reprint.', 5.29, 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0515125601.01.THUMBZZZ.jpg', 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0515125601.01.MZZZZZZZ.jpg', 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0515125601.01.LZZZZZZZ.jpg'),
                                                                                    ('Lincoln', '0375708766', 672, '2/15/2000', 180, '"The portrait is reasoned, judicious, straightforward and utterly convincing."THE NEW YORK TIMES BOOK REVIEWIn this profoundly moving work of epic proportion and intense human sympathy, Abraham Lincoln is observed by his loved ones, his rivals, and his future assassins. In this brilliantly realized, vividly imagined work of fiction, Gore Vidal gives us a portrait of America''s great president that is at once intimate and public, stark and complex, and that will become for future generations the living Lincoln, the definitive Lincoln."Richly entertaining....For the general reader the elegant explication of the issues of the day gives hearty satisfaction: history lessons with the blood still hot."THE WASHINGTON POST', 4.99, 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0375708766.01.THUMBZZZ.jpg', 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0375708766.01.MZZZZZZZ.jpg', 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0375708766.01.LZZZZZZZ.jpg'),
                                                                                    ('Comfort Me with Apples: More Adventures at the Table', '0375758739', 302, '4/9/2002', 143, 'In the sequel to Tender at the Bone, the noted food critic describes her odyssey from chef to food writer, traces her journey through restaurants from Bangkok to Paris to Los Angeles, and offers colorful anecdotes about her life and encounters with great food. 75,000 first printing.', 4.99, 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0375758739.01.THUMBZZZ.jpg', 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0375758739.01.MZZZZZZZ.jpg', 'http://images.amazon.com/images/P/0375758739.01.LZZZZZZZ.jpg'),
